|1619]] || May to September || [[Tax resistance]] by [[Guilds of Brussels]].<ref>Paul Arblaster, ''From Ghent to Aix: How They Brought the News in the Habsburg Netherlands'' (Leiden and Boston, 2014), p. 76. [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=900427684X Partial view] on [[Google Books]].</ref>\n|-\n| [[1620 in Belgium|1620]] || 19 February || First Flemish newspaper, ''[[Nieuwe Tijdinghen]]'', begins regular publication.<ref>Paul Arblaster, ''From Ghent to Aix: How They Brought the News in the Habsburg Netherlands'' (Leiden and Boston, 2014), p. 4. [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=900427684X Partial view] on [[Google Books]].</ref>\n|-\n| || 3 May || [[Chamber of Rhetoric]] [[Peoene|De Peoene]] hosts a rhetoric competition in [[Mechelen]].<ref>''De Schadt-kiste der philosophen ende poeten'' (Mechelen, [[Henry Jaye]], 1621)</ref>\n|-\n| [[1621 in Belgium|1621]] || April || [[Twelve Years' Truce]] expires.\n|-\n| || 13 July || Death of [[Albert VII, Archduke of Austria]]; [[Spanish Netherlands]] revert to [[Philip IV of Spain]]; [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]] remains in Brussels as Governess General\n|-\n| [[1622 in Belgium|1622]] || 29 August || [[Battle of Fleurus (1622)|Battle of Fleurus]]: [[Army of Flanders]] defeats Protestant German invasion force.\n|-\n| [[1629 in Belgium|1629]] || 30 April to 14 September || [[Siege of 's-Hertogenbosch]]: one of the four chief cities of the [[Duchy of Brabant]] falls to the [[Dutch Republic]].\n|-\n| [[1632 in Belgium|1632]] || || Political crisis: [[Conspiracy of Nobles (1632)|Conspiracy of Nobles]] and [[Capture of Maastricht|Siege of Maastricht]] prompt [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]], Governess General of the Spanish Netherlands, to summon the final session of the [[Estates General of 1632|Estates General]].<ref>[[Louis Prosper Gachard]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=qMtSAAAAcAAJ Actes des \u00c9tats G\u00e9n\u00e9raux de 1632]'', vol. 1 (Brussels, 1853), pp. 3\u20135.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1633 in Belgium|1633]] || 1 December || Death of [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]]\n|-\n| [[1634 in Belgium|1634]] || 4 November || Arrival of [[Cardinal-Infante Ferdinand of Austria]] as new governor general.<ref>{{Royal Collection|400100|Description of ''The Battle of N\u00f6rdlingen'' (1634)|[[Jan van den Hoecke]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1635 in Belgium|1635]] || May to July || Beginning of hostilities in the [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u201359)]]: [[Battle of Les Avins]], [[Sack of Tienen]], [[Siege of Leuven]]\n|-\n| [[1637 in Belgium|1637]] || 17 April || Exiled Dutch nobleman [[Ren\u00e9 de Renesse, 1st Count of Warfus\u00e9e]], has the mayor of Li\u00e8ge, [[S\u00e9bastien de La Ruelle]], murdered by Spanish soldiers.<ref>[[Henri Lonchay]], \"La Ruelle (S\u00e9bastien de)\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www2.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2052.pdf vol. 11] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220100252/http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2052.pdf |date=20 December 2016 }} (Brussels, 1891), 374.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1638 in Belgium|1638]] || 24 May to 16 July || [[Siege of Saint-Omer]]: French army fails to take the city of [[Saint-Omer]]\n|-\n| || 20 June || [[Battle of Kallo]]: [[Cardinal-Infante Ferdinand of Austria]] prevents Dutch forces from encircling [[Antwerp]].\n|-\n| [[1639 in Belgium|1639]] || 7 June || [[Relief of Thionville]]: imperial forces under [[Ottavio Piccolomini]] break the French siege of [[Thionville]] in the [[Duchy of Luxembourg]]\n|-\n| [[1648 in Belgium|1648]] || 15 May || [[Peace of M\u00fcnster]] ends the war with the [[Dutch Republic]].\n|-\n| [[1658 in Belgium|1658]] || 14 June || [[Battle of the Dunes (1658)|Battle of the Dunes]]: the [[Army of Flanders]] and British Royalist allies fail to raise the French-Cromwellian [[Siege of Dunkirk (1658)|Siege of Dunkirk]], leading to the loss of the city.\n|-\n| [[1695 in Belgium|1695]] || 2 July to 1 September || [[Siege of Namur (1695)|Siege of Namur]]\n|-\n| || 13\u201315 August || [[Bombardment of Brussels]] by the army of [[Louis XIV]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== 18th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1704 || 20 June || Edict in the name of [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor]], reorganises office of [[Civil law notary|notary]] in the Habsburg Netherlands.<ref>A. Libois, \"Huwelijkskontrakt tussen Amand Thirion en Marie Joseph Fontaine, 1733\", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 234\u2013241.</ref>\n|-\n| 1713 || 29 January || Second [[Barrier Treaty]] confirms the closing of the Scheldt.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\">J. Mertens, \"Oostende \u2013 Kanton \u2013 Oostende, 1719\u20131720\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 224\u2013228.</ref>\n|-\n| 1714 || 6 March || [[Treaty of Rastatt]] signed: hostilities between France and Austria arising from [[War of the Spanish Succession]] cease; [[Spanish Netherlands]] become [[Austrian Netherlands]].<ref>M. Soenen, \"Gedrukte tekst van het Verdrag van Rastadt, 1714\", tr. M. Erkens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 219\u2013222.</ref>\n|-\n| 1715 || || Start of Flemish China trade.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n| 1719 || 5 February || The ''Saint-Joseph'' sets sail from [[Ostend]] for [[Guangzhou|Canton]].<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n|  || 3 August || The ''Saint-Joseph'', from [[Ostend]], arrives in [[Guangzhou|Canton]].<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n|  || 19 September || [[Frans Anneessens]], dean of the masons' guild, beheaded in Brussels for resisting innovations in city government detrimental to the power of the [[guilds of Brussels]].<ref>[[Alphonse Wauters]], \"Anneessens, Fran\u00e7ois\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www2.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2037.pdf vol. 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802053251/http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2037.pdf |date=2 August 2017 }} (Brussels, 1866), 300\u2013317.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 27 November || The ''Saint-Joseph'', from [[Ostend]], sets sail from [[Guangzhou|Canton]] laden with tea, porcelain, silk and Chinese roots.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n| 1720 || 3 June || The ''Saint-Joseph'' reaches its home port of [[Ostend]] from a voyage to [[Guangzhou|Canton]].<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n| 1722 || 19 December || [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor]] grants a charter to the [[Ostend Company]] to trade with the Indies.<ref>[[Henri Pirenne]], ''Geschiedenis van Belgi\u00eb'', Vol. 5: ''Het einde van het Spaansch stelsel. Het Oostenrijksch stelsel. De Brabantsche omwenteling en de Luiksche omwenteling'' (Ghent, 1929), [http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/pire002gesc05_01/pire002gesc05_01_0009.php p. 195] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402102233/http://www.dbnl.org/tekst/pire002gesc05_01/pire002gesc05_01_0009.php |date=2 April 2015 }}.</ref>\n|-\n| 1723 || 11\u201312 August || Shares in the [[Ostend Company]] issued on Antwerp Exchange.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n| 1727 || 18 July || [[Ostend Company]] petitions for the harbour of Ostend to be deepened.<ref>J. Mertens, \"Dossier van werken in de haven van Oostende, 1727\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 233\u2013234.</ref>\n|-\n| 1734 || 16 February || [[Ostend Company]] officially ceases trading in accordance with the [[Treaty of Vienna (1731)]].<ref>L. Michielsen, \"Het einde van de Oostendsche Kompagnie\", ''Bijdragen tot de Geschiedenis'' 28 (1937), 128\u2013129.</ref>\n|-\n| 1737 || 16 February || [[Ostend Company]] officially wound up.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n| 1771 || 7 January || Privy Council grants necessary permits for artillery general [[Joseph de Ferraris]] to chart Mechelen and Brabant.<ref>W. Buntinx, \"Vervaardiging van de kaart van de Zuidelijke Nederlanden genaamd 'Kaart van Ferraris', 1771\u20131777\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 251\u2013254.</ref>\n|-\n| 1778 || 6 August || Government edict regulating registration of baptisms, weddings and funerals: parish priests ordered to ensure that registrations of baptisms include the child's date of birth and the parents' places of birth; of weddings include the full names, status, place of birth and place of residence of the parties; of funerals include the date and time of death; and that a copy of each year's new entries in the [[parish register]] be deposited with the provincial authorities every January.<ref name=\"A. Libois 1980 pp. 179\"/>\n|-\n| [[1780 in Belgium|1780]] || 29 November || Death of [[Maria Theresa]].\n|-\n| [[1782 in Belgium|1782]] || 1 August || [[Council of Luxembourg]] becomes a \"sovereign\" court: its legal decisions can no longer be appealed to the [[Great Council of Mechelen]].<ref name=\"R. Petit 1980 pp. 132\"/>\n|-\n| [[1787 in Belgium|1787]] || 1 January || [[Joseph II, Holy Roman Emperor]], decrees the abolition of the [[Council of Brabant]] and the institution of new law courts for the [[Duchy of Brabant]],<ref name=Stobbeleir>D. De Stobbeleir, \"Verzet tegen de hervormingen van Jozef II en de staatsgreep van 18 juni 1789\", tr. M. Erkens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 262\u2013267.</ref> to take effect from 1 May 1787.<ref>\"Causes of the discontents in the Austrian Netherlands\", ''[[The Annual Register]]'' 29 (1789), [https://books.google.com/books?id=pcWT254cXPcC&pg=PA208 p. 208] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624170017/https://books.google.com/books?id=pcWT254cXPcC&pg=PA208 |date=24 June 2016 }}.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 20 April || [[Council of Brabant]] declares its abolition unconstitutional.<ref name=Stobbeleir/>\n|-\n| || 21 September || Joseph II's interim minister plenipotentiary, [[Sir Joseph Murray, 3rd Baronet]], postpones the abolition of the Council of Brabant.<ref name=Stobbeleir/>\n|-\n| [[1788 in Belgium|1788]] || 22 January || Council of Brabant refuses to issue a new decree by Joseph II's minister plenipotentiary, [[Ferdinand von Trauttmansdorff]].<ref name=Stobbeleir/>\n|-\n| [[1789 in Belgium|1789]] || 26 August || [[Republic of Li\u00e8ge]] proclaimed.<ref>Bruno Demoulin, ''Recueil des instructions aux ambassadeurs et ministres de France'' (Principaut\u00e9 de Li\u00e8ge 31; 1998), p. xxxviii.</ref>\n|-\n| || October || Army of [[\u00e9migr\u00e9]] volunteers invades the Austrian Netherlands.<ref name=Stobbeleir/> [[Manifesto of the People of Brabant]] published. Government forces defeated in [[Battle of Turnhout (1789)]].\n|-\n| [[1790 in Belgium|1790]] || 4 January || [[Manifesto of the Province of Flanders]]: [[States of Flanders]] repudiate loyalty to the [[count of Flanders]] and the [[Austrian Habsburgs|House of Austria]] and declare the old [[County of Flanders]] an independent sovereign state\n|-\n| || 11 January || [[United States of Belgium]] proclaimed.\n|-\n| || 22 September || [[Battle of Falmagne]]: short-lived restoration of Austrian rule in the Low Countries\n|-\n| [[1791 in Belgium|1791]] || 13 February || Austrian military intervention restores [[C\u00e9sar-Constantin-Fran\u00e7ois de Hoensbroeck]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| [[1792 in Belgium|1792]] || 16 November || [[Battle of Jemappes]]: French gain control of Belgium and Li\u00e8ge.\n|-\n| [[1793 in Belgium|1793]] || 18 March || [[Battle of Neerwinden (1793)|Battle of Neerwinden]]: short-lived restoration of Austrian rule in the Low Countries.\n|-\n|  || 12\u201313 September || [[Battle of Menin (1793)|Battle of Menin]] between French and Dutch forces\n|-\n|  || 15 September || [[Battle of Courtrai (1793)|First Battle of Courtrai]] between French and Austrian forces\n|-\n| [[1794 in Belgium|1794]] || 26 June || [[Battle of Fleurus (1794)|Battle of Fleurus]]: decisive French victory in the [[Flanders Campaign]] of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]].\n|-\n| || 17\u201318 September || [[Battle of Sprimont]]: final Austrian defeat in the Low Countries\n|-\n| [[1795 in Belgium|1795]] || 1 October || Former [[Austrian Netherlands]] and [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]] unilaterally annexed to the [[French First Republic]].<ref name=\"Trajecta 9 2000\">[[Jan Roegiers]], \"Revolutie in de seminaries\", ''Trajecta'' 9 (2000), 112\u2013133.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 6 November || Decree of [[French Republican Calendar|14 Brumaire, Year IV]] brings into force in Belgium the French laws of 1791 abolishing craft guilds.<ref name=\"A. Graffart 1980 p. 270\">A. Graffart, \"Register van het schilders-, goudslagers- en glazenmakersambacht van Brussel, 1707\u20131794\", tr. M. Erkens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), p. 270.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1796 in Belgium|1796]] || 17 June || Decree of [[French Republican Calendar|29 Prairial, Year IV]] establishes civil registration of births, marriages and deaths throughout what is now Belgium.<ref name=\"A. Libois 1980 pp. 179\"/>\n|-\n|  || August || Moveables and archives of the [[guilds of Brussels]] sold at public auction on the [[Grand Place]].<ref name=\"A. Graffart 1980 p. 270\"/>\n|-\n| [[1797 in Belgium|1797]] ||  || Suppression of religious life begins in earnest.<ref name=\"Trajecta 9 2000\"/>\n|-\n|  || 28 June || \u00c9cole Centrale for the [[Escaut (department)|Department of the Scheldt]] inaugurated in Ghent.<ref>''Proc\u00e8s-verbal de l'inauguration de l'\u00c9cole Centrale du D\u00e9partement de l'Escaut, et discours prononc\u00e9s \u00e0 ce sujet'