|date=1894|pages=76\u201384|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/phlou_0776-5541_1894_num_1_1_1363}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1881 in Belgium|1881]] || 6 March || Review ''[[L'Art Moderne]]'' begins publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://digitheque.ulb.ac.be/fr/digitheque-revues-litteraires-belges/periodiques-numerises/index.html#c11373 |website=P\u00e9riodiques num\u00e9ris\u00e9s dans le cadre de l'Action de Recherche Concert\u00e9e|author=Ren\u00e9 Fayt|title=R\u00e9sum\u00e9|publisher=[[Universit\u00e9 libre de Bruxelles]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1882 in Belgium|1882]] || 6 May || [[North Sea Fisheries Convention]] signed, to come into effect in 1884.\n|-\n| || 13 June || [[Belgian general election, 1882|Partial legislative elections of 1882]]\n|-\n| || 31 July || [[D\u00e9sir\u00e9-Joseph Mercier]] appointed to the new chair in [[Thomist philosophy]] at the [[Catholic University of Leuven (1835\u20131968)|Catholic University of Louvain]].<ref>Robert Wielockx, \"De Mercier \u00e0 De Wulf: D\u00e9buts de l'\u00c9cole de Louvain\", in ''Gli studi di filosofia medievale fra otto e novecento'', edited by Ruedi Imbach and Alfonso Maier\u00f9 (Rome, 1991), p. 77. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Vt8auvixafcC&pg=PA77 Preview on Google Books]</ref>\n|-\n| [[1883 in Belgium|1883]] || 28 October || Founding meeting of the art association [[Les XX]]\n|-\n| [[1884 in Belgium|1884]] || 16 June || [[Jules Malou]] replaces [[Walth\u00e8re Fr\u00e8re-Orban]] as Prime Minister \n|-\n| || June and July || [[Belgian general election, 1884]]\n|-\n| || 26 October || [[Auguste Beernaert]] replaces [[Jules Malou]] as Prime Minister \n|-\n| [[1885 in Belgium|1885]] || 6 April || Inaugural meeting of the [[Belgian Labour Party]] held in Brussels\n|-\n| || 2 May to 2 November || [[Exposition Universelle d'Anvers (1885)|World Exhibition in Antwerp]]\n|-\n| [[1886 in Belgium|1886]] || 18\u201329 March || [[Belgian strike of 1886|Series of strikes and disturbances]] in industrial areas of Wallonia\n|-\n| || 8 June || [[Belgian general election, 1886|Partial legislative elections of 1886]]\n|-\n| [[1888 in Belgium|1888]] || 12 June || [[Belgian general election, 1888|Partial legislative elections of 1888]]\n|-\n| [[1889 in Belgium|1889]] || 15 April || Death of [[Father Damien]]\n|-\n| [[1890 in Belgium|1890]] || 10 June || [[Belgian general election, 1890|Partial legislative elections of 1890]]\n|-\n| || 8 November || Composer [[C\u00e9sar Franck]] dies\n|-\n| [[1892 in Belgium|1892]] || 14 June || [[Belgian general election, 1892]]\n|-\n| [[1893 in Belgium|1893]] || 12\u201318 April ||[[Belgian general strike of 1893|General strike]] demanding an extension of the franchise\n|-\n| || 15 April || Inaugural meeting of the [[Christene Volkspartij]] held in [[Okegem]], with a party programme drafted by [[Adolf Daens]]\n|-\n| [[1894 in Belgium|1894]] || 26 March || [[Jules de Burlet]] replaces [[Auguste Beernaert]] as Prime Minister \n|-\n| || 5 May to 5 November || [[Exposition Internationale d'Anvers (1894)|International Exposition]] (world's fair) in Antwerp\n|-\n| || 14 October || [[Belgian general election, 1894]]\n|-\n| [[1896 in Belgium|1896]] || 25 February || [[Paul de Smet de Naeyer]] replaces [[Jules de Burlet]] as Prime Minister \n|-\n| || 5 and 12 July || [[Belgian general election, 1896|Partial legislative elections of 1896]]\n|-\n| [[1897 in Belgium|1897]] || 10 May to 8 November || [[Brussels International Exposition (1897)|Exposition Internationale]] (world's fair) held in Brussels\n|-\n| [[1898 in Belgium|1898]] || 22 May || [[Belgian general election, 1898|Partial legislative elections of 1898]]\n|-\n| [[1899 in Belgium|1899]] || 24 January || [[Jules Vandenpeereboom]] replaces [[Paul de Smet de Naeyer]] as Prime Minister\n|-\n| || 5 August ||  [[Paul de Smet de Naeyer]] replaces [[Jules Vandenpeereboom]] as Prime Minister\n|-\n| || 3 December || [[Antoon Stillemans]], [[bishop of Ghent]], suspends [[Adolf Daens]] as a diocesan priest due to his political activism<ref>Jan de Maeyer, ''Arthur Verhaegen, 1847\u20131917: de rode baron'' (Leuven University Press, 1994), p. 306.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1900 in Belgium|1900]] || 27 May || [[Belgian general election, 1900]]\n|-\n| || 2 October || Wedding of King [[Albert I of Belgium]] and [[Elisabeth of Bavaria, Queen of Belgium|Elisabeth of Bavaria]].\n|}\n\n== 20th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| [[1901 in Belgium|1901]] || 3 November || Birth of future king [[Leopold III of Belgium]].\n|-\n| [[1902 in Belgium|1902]] || 25 May || [[Belgian general election, 1902|Partial legislative elections]]\n|-\n|  || 15 November || Italian anarchist [[Gennaro Rubino]] attempts to assassinate Leopold II\n|-\n| [[1904 in Belgium|1904]] || 1 May || [[Belgium national football team]] play their first official game, against France.\n|-\n|  || 29 May || [[Belgian general election, 1904|Partial legislative elections]]\n|-\n| [[1905 in Belgium|1905]] || 27 April to 6 November || [[Li\u00e8ge International (1905)|Exposition Universelle et Internationale de Li\u00e8ge]] takes place.<ref>''Li\u00e8ge et l'Exposition universelle de 1905'', edited by Christine Renardy (Brussels, 2005).</ref>\n|-\n| [[1906 in Belgium|1906]] || 27 May || [[Belgian general election, 1906|Partial legislative elections]]\n|-\n| [[1907 in Belgium|1907]] || 23 July || [[Port of Zeebrugge]] formally opened.\n|-\n| [[1908 in Belgium|1908]] || 24 May || [[Belgian general election, 1908|Partial legislative elections]]\n|-\n|  || 15 November || Belgium assumes sovereignty of the Congo under the [[Colonial Charter on the Belgian annexation of the Congo Free State]]\n|-\n| [[1909 in Belgium|1909]] || 17 December || Death of [[Leopold II of Belgium|Leopold II]], King of the Belgians\n|-\n|  || 23 December || Accession of [[Albert I of Belgium|Albert I]] as King of the Belgians\n|-\n| [[1910 in Belgium|1910]] || 23 April to 1 November || [[Brussels 