n Belgium|1939]] || 2 April || [[Belgian general election, 1939]]\n|-\n|  || 30 July || [[Exposition internationale de l'eau]] opens in [[Li\u00e8ge]].\n|-\n| [[1940 in Belgium|1940]] || 10 May || German invasion: beginning of Belgian involvement in the [[Second World War]].\n|-\n| [[1941 in Belgium|1941]] || 11 September || King [[Leopold III of Belgium|Leopold III]] secretly marries [[Lilian, Princess of R\u00e9thy|Lilian Baels]]\n|-\n| [[1944 in Belgium|1944]] || 4 September || Liberation of Brussels and Antwerp.\n|-\n|  || 5 September || Customs Convention between Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg signed.<ref name=Panhuys>H.F. van Panhuys, L.J. Brinkhorst, and H.H. Maas (eds.), ''International Organisation and Integration'' (Deventer and Leyden, 1968).</ref>{{rp|978}}\n|-\n| || 16 December || German reinvasion: the [[Battle of the Bulge]] begins.\n|-\n| [[1945 in Belgium|1945]] || 25 January || Liberation of Belgium completed.\n|-\n|  || 8 May || [[End of World War II in Europe]].\n|-\n| [[1946 in Belgium|1946]] || 17 February || [[Belgian general election, 1946]]\n|-\n|  || 12 April || Flemish nationalist leader [[August Borms]] executed by firing squad as a collaborator\n|-\n| [[1947 in Belgium|1947]] || 8 September || [[Victor Horta]] dies.\n|-\n| [[1948 in Belgium|1948]] || 1 January || Customs Convention between Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg comes into force.{{r|Panhuys|p=978}}\n|-\n|  || 17 March || Belgium, France, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom sign the [[Treaty of Brussels]], establishing the [[Brussels Pact]] for economic, social and cultural collaboration and collective self-defence.{{r|Panhuys|p=905}}\n|-\n|  || 25 August || [[Treaty of Brussels]], establishing the [[Brussels Pact]] for economic, social and cultural collaboration and collective self-defence, comes into effect.{{r|Panhuys|p=905}}\n|-\n| [[1949 in Belgium|1949]] || 26 June || [[Belgian general election, 1949]]\n|-\n| [[1950 in Belgium|1950]] || 12 March || [[Royal Question]] brought to a head with [[Belgian monarchy referendum, 1950]]\n|-\n|  || 4 June || [[Belgian general election, 1950]]\n|-\n| [[1951 in Belgium|1951]] || 18 April || [[Treaty of Paris (1951)|Treaty of Paris]] signed, establishing the [[European Coal and Steel Community]].{{r|Panhuys|p=655}}\n|-\n| || 16 July || King Leopold III abdicates\n|-\n| || 17 July || [[Baudouin of Belgium]] sworn in as king\n|-\n| [[1952 in Belgium|1952]] || 25 July || [[Treaty of Paris (1951)|Treaty of Paris]] establishing the [[European Coal and Steel Community]] comes into force.{{r|Panhuys|p=655}}\n|-\n| [[1953 in Belgium|1953]] || 31 January to 1 February || [[North Sea flood of 1953|North Sea flood]] damages Belgian coastal defences, killing 28\n|-\n| [[1954 in Belgium|1954]] || 11 April || [[Belgian general election, 1954]]\n|-\n|  || 23 October || Paris Protocol agreed, transforming the [[Brussels Pact]] into the [[Western European Union]] (with Germany and Italy joining).{{r|Panhuys|p=905}}\n|-\n| [[1955 in Belgium|1955]] || 6 May || Paris Protocol transforming the [[Brussels Pact]] into the [[Western European Union]] comes into effect.{{r|Panhuys|p=905}}\n|-\n|  || 5 November || Convention establishing the Interparliamentary Consultative Council of the [[Benelux]].{{r|Panhuys|p=978}}\n|-\n| [[1956 in Belgium|1956]] || 7 June || Labour Treaty signed at The Hague establishing [[freedom of movement|free movement of labour]] between Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands, to come into force 1 November 1960.<ref>Daniel C. Turack, \"Freedom of Movement and the Travel Document in Benelux\", ''[[International and Comparative Law Quarterly]]'', 17:1 (Jan. 1968), pp. 197-198.</ref>\n|-\n| || 8 August || [[Mining accident of Marcinelle]] claims 262 lives, including 136 Italian [[foreign worker]]s\n|-\n| [[1957 in Belgium|1957]] || 25 March || Belgium a signatory to the [[Treaty of Rome]] establishing the [[European Economic Community]].\n|-\n| [[1958 in Belgium|1958]] || 17 April to 19 October || [[Expo 58]], the first major World\u2019s Fair since the Second World War.\n|-\n|  || 1 June || [[1958 Belgian general election]]\n|-\n| [[1960 in Belgium|1960]] || 15 April || Birth of future King [[Philippe of Belgium]]\n|-\n| || June || [[Belgian Congo]] becomes independent; on the eve of the celebrations [[Ambroise Boimbo]] snatches the ceremonial sabre of King Baudouin.\n|-\n|  || 1 November || Treaty establishing [[Benelux Economic Union]] comes into force, providing for the free movement of persons, goods, capital and services between Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg.{{r|Panhuys|p=978}}\n|-\n| [[1961 in Belgium|1961]] || 17 January || [[Patrice Lumumba]] killed in Congo\n|-\n|  || 26 March || [[1961 Belgian general election]]\n|-\n| | [[1962 in Belgium|1962]] || 14 October || Rioting in Brussels between Flemish nationalist and Francophone demonstrators.<ref>{{Cite news|title=20 Wounded in Brussels Word Riots|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|url=http://archives.chicagotribune.com/1962/10/15/page/1/article/20-wounded-in-brussels-word-riots|date=15 October 1962|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1963 in Belgium|1963]] || || Jeanne Deckers, [[the Singing Nun]], becomes world famous.\n|-\n| [[1964 in Belgium|1964]] ||  || [[Salvatore Adamo]] becomes one of the most commercially successful musicians in the world.\n|-\n| [[1965 in Belgium|1965]] || 31 March || Treaty to establish a Benelux Court of Justice signed.{{r|Panhuys|p=978}}\n|-\n|  || 23 May || [[1965 Belgian general election]]\n|-\n| [[1966 in Belgium|1966]] || 10 February || Belgium ratifies [[London Fisheries Convention]].\n|-\n|  || 15 March || [[London Fisheries Convention]] regulating fisheries in the North Sea comes into force.\n|-\n| [[1968 in Belgium|1968]] || 31 March || [[1968 Belgian general election]]\n|-\n|  || 24 June || [[Split of the Catholic University of Leuven]] announced.\n|-\n| [[1971 in Belgium|1971]] || 29 September to 1 October || Emperor [[