 of [[Genk Body & Assembly|Ford Genk]] announced, to be completed in 2014 with loss of over 4,000 jobs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20121024_007|date=24 October 2012|title=Ford Genk sluit in 2014|newspaper=[[De Standaard]]|language=nl|accessdate=1 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811190154/http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20121024_007|archive-date=11 August 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[2013 in Belgium|2013]] || 21 July || [[Philippe of Belgium|Philippe]] becomes 7th king of the Belgians\n|-\n| [[2014 in Belgium|2014]] || 24 May || [[Jewish Museum of Belgium shooting]] kills four\n|-\n|  || 25 May || [[Belgian federal election, 2014]]\n|-\n| [[2015 in Belgium|2015]] || 6 November || [[Jozef De Kesel]] succeeds [[Andr\u00e9-Joseph L\u00e9onard]] as [[archbishop of Mechelen-Brussels]]\n|-\n| || 21 to 25 November || [[Brussels lockdown]]\n|-\n| [[2016 in Belgium|2016]] || 22 March || [[2016 Brussels bombings]]\n|-\n|  || 20 December || Publifin scandal breaks in ''[[Le Vif/L'Express]]''\n|-\n| [[2017 in Belgium|2017]] || 31 May || Samusocial scandal breaks in [[Parliament of the Brussels-Capital Region|Brussels parliament]]\n|-\n| [[2018 in Belgium|2018]] || 9 December || [[Michel I Government]] splits, to be succeeded by [[Michel II Government]], after division over endorsement of the [[Global Compact for Migration]]\n|-\n| [[2019 in Belgium|2019]] || 26 May || [[2019 Belgian federal election]]\n|-\n|}\n{{History of the Low Countries}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of Belgium]]\n** [[History of Wallonia]]\n** [[History of Flanders]]\n** [[History of the Jews in Belgium]]\n* [[Timeline of Burgundian and Habsburg acquisitions in the Low Countries]]\n* [[List of Belgian historians]]\n\n;Cities in Belgium\n* [[Timeline of Antwerp]]\n* [[Timeline of Bruges]]\n* [[Timeline of Brussels]]\n* [[Timeline of Ghent]]\n* [[Timeline of Leuven]]\n* [[Timeline of Li\u00e8ge]]\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}