Biografisch Woordenboek]]'', vol. 3 (Brussels, 1968), 484\u2013489.</ref>\n|-\n| 717 || || See of Maastricht moved to the location of [[Lambert of Maastricht]]'s murder, now [[Li\u00e8ge]].\n|-\n| 727 || 30 May || Death of [[Hubertus]], [[Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=17}}\n|-\n| 748 || 2 April || Birth of [[Charlemagne]], first [[Holy Roman Emperor]].<ref>[[Janet Nelson]], ''King and Emperor: A New Life of Charlemagne'' (London, Allen Lane, 2019), p. 24.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== 9th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 819 || 13 April || [[Louis the Pious]] confirms the liberties granted to [[St Bavo's Cathedral, Ghent|St Bavo's Abbey]] by [[Charlemagne]] (oldest extant original charter in a Belgian archive)<ref>C. Vleeschouwers, \"Diploma van keizer Lodewijk de Vrome voor de Sint-Baafsabdij te Gent, 819\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 ([[State Archives in Belgium]], Brussels, 1980), pp. 3\u20136.</ref>\n|-\n| 820 ||  || First recorded [[Viking]] raid on the Flemish coast.{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 825 || 30 September|| The remains of [[Hubertus|St Hubert]] (died 727) installed in the monastery that would become the [[Abbey of Saint-Hubert]].<ref>P. Bertrand, \"Hubert (Saint)\", in ''Dictionnaire d'histoire et de g\u00e9ographie eccl\u00e9siastiques'', vol. 25 (Paris: Letouzey et An\u00e9, 1995), 23\u201324.</ref>\n|-\n| 843 || August || [[Treaty of Verdun]] divides the [[Carolingian Empire]] between the three sons of [[Louis the Pious]]: [[Lothair I]], [[Louis the German]] and  [[Charles the Bald]], creating the kingdom of [[Middle Francia]] (including most of the [[Low Countries]]) for Lothair and assigning [[County of Flanders|Flanders]] to Charles the Bald.\n|-\n| 850 ||  || Norsemen raid Flanders.{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 855 ||  || [[Treaty of Pr\u00fcm]] divides [[Middle Francia]] into the [[kingdom of Lotharingia]] (including most of the [[Low Countries]]), the [[kingdom of Arles]] and the [[Kingdom of Italy (Holy Roman Empire)|kingdom of Italy]].\n|-\n| 861 ||  || Norsemen raid Flanders.{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 864 ||  || Norsemen raid Flanders.{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 870 ||  || [[Treaty of Meerssen]] partitions [[Lotharingia]] (including most of the [[Low Countries]]) between [[East Francia]] (Germany) and [[West Francia]] (France).\n|-\n| 879 ||  || Norsemen raid [[Toxandri|Taxandria]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 880 ||  || Norsemen raid [[Tournaisis]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 881 ||  || Norsemen plunder [[Cambrai]] and encamp near [[Maastricht]], extorting tribute from Maastricht, [[Tongeren]], [[Li\u00e8ge]], [[Sint-Truiden]], [[Malmedy]], [[Stavelot]], and [[Pr\u00fcm]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=38}}\n|-\n| 891 || September or October || Norse invaders defeated in [[Battle of Leuven (891)|Battle on the Dijle]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=39}}\n|-\n| 895 ||  || [[Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Arnulf of Carinthia]] appoints his illegitimate son [[Zwentibold]] as king of [[Lotharingia]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=42-43}}\n|-\n| 900 || 13 August || [[Zwentibold]] slain by Count [[Reginar, Duke of Lorraine|Reginar I of Hainault]]; [[Lotharingia]] reincorporated into [[East Francia]].\n|-\n|}\n\n== 10th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 908 ||  || [[Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]] granted right to levy a toll in [[Maastricht]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=57}}\n|-\n| 910 ||  || Count [[Reginar, Duke of Lorraine|Reginar I of Hainault]] appointed [[margrave]] of [[Lotharingia]]; historically regarded as the first Duke of Lorraine.\n|-\n| 915 ||  || Death of [[Reginar, Duke of Lorraine]], at his palace in [[Meerssen]]; succeeded by his son [[Gilbert, Duke of Lorraine|Giselbert]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=45}}\n|-\n| 918 || 10 September || Death of [[Baldwin II, Margrave of Flanders]] at [[Blandijnberg]]; succeeded by his son [[Arnulf I, Count of Flanders|Arnulf]].\n|-\n| 925 ||  || [[Henry the Fowler]] invades Lotharingia and receives oaths of loyalty from the local aristocracy.{{r|Pirenne1|p=46}}\n|-\n| 936 || 7 August || [[Gilbert, Duke of Lorraine]], attends the coronation of [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto I]] in [[Aachen]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=47}}\n|-\n| 939 || 2 October || [[Battle of Andernach]]: death of [[Gilbert, Duke of Lorraine]]; end of independence of Lotharingia (referred to as \"Belgica\" in the 10th-century histories of [[Richer of Rheims]]).{{r|Pirenne1|p=46n2}}<ref>Richerus of Rheims, ''Histoire de son temps'', edited by G.-H. Pertz, translated and annotated by J. Guadet, [https://books.google.fr/books?id=2dDOIVH3g68C vol. 1] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306225720/https://books.google.fr/books?id=2dDOIVH3g68C |date=6 March 2016 }} (Paris, 1845), pp. 72, 82.</ref>\n|-\n| around 940 || || [[Saint-Ghislain Abbey]] reformed by [[G\u00e9rard of Brogne]]\n|-\n| 948 ||  || Death of Isaac, Count of [[Cambrai]]; powers of count transferred to [[Fulbert (bishop of Cambrai)|Fulbert]], [[Bishop of Cambrai]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=55}}\n|-\n| 953 ||  || [[Bruno the Great]], [[Archbishop of Cologne]], appointed [[Duke of Lotharingia]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=55}}\n|-\n| 954 ||  || [[Hungarian invasions of Europe|Hungarian attackers]] raid [[Lower Lotharingia]], besiege [[Cambrai]].{{r|Pirenne1|p=55}}\n|-\n| 959 ||  || [[Bruno the Great]] divides [[Lotharingia]] into Upper Lotharingia (the later [[Lorraine (duchy)|Duchy of Lorraine]]) and [[Lower Lotharingia]] (the later [[Lothier|Duchy of Lothier]]).<ref name=Parisse>Michel Parisse, \"Lotharingia\", in ''New Cambridge Medieval History'', edited by [[Timothy Reuter]], vol. 3 (Cambridge, 1999).</ref>{{rp|318\u2013319}}\n|-\n|  || 3 October || Death of [[Gerard of Brogne]].\n|-\n| 964 ||  || [[Godfrey I, Duke of Lower Lorraine]], dies in Italy; no immediate successor.\n|-\n| 965 || 28 March || Death of [[Arnulf I, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Arnulf II, Count of Flanders]]\n|-\n|  || 2 June || [[Otto I, Holy Roman Emperor]], confirms [[Godfrey I, Duke of Lower Lorraine|Godfrey of Lower Lotharingia's]] gift to [[Saint-Ghislain Abbey]] of 18 [[mansus|mansi]] of land in [[Villers-Saint-Ghislain]].<ref>D. Van Overstraeten, \"Diploma van keizer Otto I voor de abdij van Saint-Ghislain, 965\", tr. C. Vleeschouwers, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 ([[State Archives in Belgium]], Brussels, 1980), pp. 10\u201313.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 11 October || Death of [[Bruno the Great]], [[Duke of Lotharingia]].\n|-\n| 966 || 5 May || [[Lothair of France|Lothar, King of the Franks]], confirms the possessions of [[St. Peter's Abbey, Ghent]], including those bequeathed by [[Arnulf I, Count of Flanders]], and contested by his heirs.<ref>G. Mar\u00e9chal, \"Bekrachtiging van de goederen van de Gentse Sint-Pietersabdij\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 10\u201313.</ref>\n|-\n| 968 ||  || [[Richar, Duke of Lower Lorraine|Richar, Count of Mons]], appointed Duke of Lower Lotharingia.\n|-\n| 973 ||  || [[Richar, Duke of Lower Lotharingia]], dies; no immediate successor.\n|-\n| 977 ||  || [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor]], appoints [[Charles, Duke of Lower Lorraine|Charles]], brother of [[Lothair of France]], as Duke of Lower Lotharingia.{{r|Parisse|p=319}}\n|-\n| 980 ||  || [[Otto II, Holy Roman Emperor]], confirms all previous endowments to [[Notker of Li\u00e8ge|Notker]], Bishop of Li\u00e8ge, and issues a general immunity for the bishopric's lands: beginning of the establishment of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]].{{r|Parisse|p=323}}\n|-\n| 985 ||  || [[Otto III, Holy Roman Emperor|Otto III]], [[King of Germany]], endows [[Notker of Li\u00e8ge|Notker]], Bishop of Li\u00e8ge, with the [[County of Huy]]: full establishment of the [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]].{{r|Parisse|p=323}}\n|-\n| 987 || 30 March || Death of [[Arnulf II, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Baldwin IV, Count of Flanders]].\n|-\n|}\n\n{{anchor|2nd millennium}}\n\n== 11th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1008 ||  || [[Baldrick II]] succeeds [[Notker of Li\u00e8ge|Notger]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1018 || 29 July || [[Battle of Vlaardingen]]: imperial forces commanded by [[Godfrey II, Duke of Lower Lorraine]], and [[Baldrick II]], [[bishop of Li\u00e8ge]], defeated by the army of [[Dirk III, Count of Holland]]. Baldrick died after a sudden illness on the journey; Godfrey was captured in the battle.\n|-\n|  || November || [[Wolbodo]] consecrated [[bishop of Li\u00e8ge]].<ref>[[Herman Vander Linden]], \"Wolbodon\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www.academieroyale.be/Academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2078.pdf vol. 27] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170403112449/http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2078.pdf |date=3 April 2017 }} (Brussels, 1938), 392\u2013394.</ref>\n|-\n| 1021 ||  || [[Durandus of Li\u00e8ge|Durandus]] succeeds [[Wolbodo]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1025 ||  || [[Reginard]] succeeds [[Durandus of Li\u00e8ge|Durandus]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1035 || 30 May || Death of [[Baldwin IV, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Baldwin V, Count of Flanders]] \n|-\n| 1037 ||  || [[Nithard of Li\u00e8ge|Nithard]] succeeds [[Reginard]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1042 ||  || [[Wazo of Li\u00e8ge|Wazo]] succeeds [[Nithard of Li\u00e8ge|Nithard]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1048 ||  || [[Theodwin of Li\u00e8ge|Theodwin]] succeeds [[Wazo of Li\u00e8ge|Wazo]] as [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1049 || 13 January || Forces of [[Theodwin of Li\u00e8ge]] defeat forces of [[Dirk IV, Count of Holland]], killing Dirk and restoring imperial authority in the [[Rhine delta]].<ref name=\"vol. 24\">Philibert Schmitz, \"Theoduin\", in ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www.academieroyale.be/Academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2072.pdf vol. 24] (Brussels, 1929), 757-758.</ref>\n|-\n| 1060 ||  || [[Baldwin V, Count of Flanders]], becomes regent of France\n|-\n| 1066 ||  || [[Theodwin of Li\u00e8ge]] grants city rights to [[Huy]], the oldest such charter to survive from what is now Belgium.<ref name=\"vol. 24\"/>\n|-\n| 1067 || 1 September || Death of [[Baldwin V, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Baldwin VI, Count of Flanders]]\n|-\n| c.1067 || || ''[[Genealogia comitum Flandrensium]]'' compiled.<ref>Georges Declercq, \"Genealogia comitum Flandrensium\", in ''Encyclopedia of the Medieval Chronicle'', edited by R. G. Dunphy (Leiden and Boston: Brill, 2010), 666\u20137.</ref>\n|-\n| 1070 || 17 July || Death of [[Baldwin VI, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Arnulf III, Count of Flanders]]\n|-\n| 1071 || 22 February || [[Battle of Cassel (1071)|Battle of Cassel]] between [[Robert I, Count of Flanders|Robert the Frisian]] and his nephew, [[Arnulf III, Count of Flanders]]. Arnulf was killed in the battle and Robert succeeded him as count.\n|-\n| 1074 || 29 April|| [[Pope Gregory VII]] issues [[papal bull|bull of protection]] for the [[Abbey of Saint-Hubert]].<ref name=\"Reform 1077 pp. 399\">[[Brigitte Meijns]], \"Papal Bulls as Instruments of Reform: the Reception of the Protection Bulls of Gregory VII in the Dioceses of Li\u00e8ge and Th\u00e9rouanne (1074\u20131077)\", ''[[Church History (journal)|Church History]]'', 87:2 (2018), pp. 399\u2013423.</ref>\n|-\n| 1075 || 23 March || [[Pope Gregory VII]] writes to [[Theodwin of Li\u00e8ge|Theodwin]], [[bishop of Li\u00e8ge]], urging him to leave the abbot of [[Abbey of Saint-Hubert|Saint-Hubert]] unmolested.<ref name=\"Reform 1077 pp. 399\"/>\n|-\n|  || 23 June || Death of [[Theodwin of Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n| 1077 || 28 April || [[Pope Gregory VII]] issues [[papal bull|bull of protection]] for [[Watten Abbey]].<ref name=\"Reform 1077 pp. 399\"/>\n|-\n| 1087 ||  || [[Godfrey of Bouillon]] becomes [[Duke of Lower Lorraine]]\n|-\n| 1093 || 13 October || Death of [[Robert I, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Robert II, Count of Flanders]]\n|-\n| 1096 || August || [[Godfrey of Bouillon]], [[Duke of Lower Lorraine]], sets off as one of the leaders of the [[First Crusade]].<ref>Alan V. Murray, [http://www.persee.fr/doc/rbph_0035-0818_1992_num_70_2_3824 The Army of Godfrey of Bouillon, 1096\u20131099: Structure and dynamics of a contingent on the First Crusade] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604062610/https://www.persee.fr/doc/rbph_0035-0818_1992_num_70_2_3824 |date=4 June 2018 }}, ''[[Revue belge de philologie et d'histoire]]'' 70/2 (1992), pp. 301\u2013329.</ref>\n|-\n| 1100 || 18 July || Death of [[Godfrey of Bouillon]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== 12th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1105 ||  || [[Baldric of Noyon]], [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Tournai|Bishop of Tournai]], awards the [[Jus patronatus#Right of presentation|right of presentment]] for [[Tielt]] to the chapter of St Salvator in [[Harelbeke]]<ref>K. Maddens, \"Schenking van het altaar van Tielt aan het Sint-Salvatorskapittel van Harelbeke, 1105\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 ([[State Archives in Belgium]], Brussels, 1980), pp. 15\u201317.</ref>\n|-\n| 1107 ||  || The hermit [[Ligerius]] founds a community that would become [[Ten Duinen Abbey]] (the Abbey of Dunes).<ref>M.-A. Dimier, \"Dunes\", in ''Dictionnaire d'histoire et de g\u00e9ographie eccl\u00e9siastiques'', vol. 14 (Paris, 1960), 1039\u20131044.</ref>\n|-\n| 1111 || 5 October || Death of [[Robert II, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Baldwin VII, Count of Flanders]]\n|-\n| 1119 || 17 July || Death of [[Baldwin VII, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Charles I, Count of Flanders]] (Charles the Good)\n|-\n| 1125 ||  || [[Godfrey I, Count of Louvain]] confirms the agreement of Ava of Waver and her sons with the [[Forest Abbey|priory of Forest]], transferring ownership of an [[allod]] in [[Woluwe]].<ref>M. Soenen, \"Verkoop allodiaal domein te Woluwe, 1125\", tr. C. Vleeschouwers, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 17\u201321.</ref>\n|-\n| 1127 || 2 March || Murder of [[Charles I, Count of Flanders|Charles the Good]], Count of Flanders\n|-\n|  || 30 March || [[William Clito]] claims countship of Flanders\n|-\n| 1128 || 28 July || [[William Clito]] dies while laying siege to [[Aalst, Belgium|Aalst]]; [[Thierry, Count of Flanders|Thierry of Alsace]] established his claim to the countship of Flanders\n|-\n| 1141 || 17 August to 22 September || Siege of [[Bouillon Castle]] by [[Albero II of Chiny-Namur|Albero]], [[prince-bishop of Li\u00e8ge]].\n|-\n| 1146 || 24 June || [[Pope Eugene III]] confirms [[Wibald]], [[Principality of Stavelot-Malmedy|Abbot of Stavelot and Malmedy]], in possession of the goods of the abbey.<ref>G. Hansotte, \"Bevestiging van de bezittingen van de abdij van Stavelot, 1146\", tr. A. Zoete, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 21\u201322.</ref>\n|-\n| 1147 || after 11 May || [[Henry II of Leez]], [[Prince-Bishopric of Li\u00e8ge|Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]], confirms [[Affligem Abbey]] in possession of its property in the diocese of Li\u00e8ge.<ref>M. Grauwen, \"Bekrachtiging der goederen van de abdij van Affligem, 1147\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 23\u201325.</ref>\n|-\n|  ||  || [[Arnout IV, Count of Aarschot]], and [[Christian of Ghistelles]], leaders of forces from the Low Countries on the [[Second Crusade]], are diverted to the [[Siege of Lisbon]]\n|-\n| 1163 || June || [[Henry IV, Count of Luxembourg|Henry the Blind]], [[Count of Namur]] and [[Count of Luxembourg|of Luxembourg]], being childless, names his sister [[Alice of Namur]] with her husband [[Baldwin IV, Count of Hainaut]], and [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut|their son Baldwin]], as heirs of all his [[allod]]ial possessions, \"with sod and twig\", retaining [[usufruct]] during his own lifetime.<ref name=\"F. Ladrier 1980 pp. 29\">F. Ladrier, \"De erfopvolging van Hendrik de Blinde, graaf van Namen, 1163\u20131184\", tr. A. Zoete, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 29\u201333.</ref>\n|-\n| 1168 || 17 January || Death of [[Thierry, Count of Flanders]]; succession of [[Philip I, Count of Flanders|Philip of Alsace]] as count of Flanders\n|-\n|  ||  || [[Godfrey III, Count of Louvain|Godfrey]], Duke of Lower Lotharingia, confirms the privileges of the borough of [[Tienen]] (oldest extant civic charter from the [[Duchy of Brabant]])<ref>A. Graffart, \"Godfried III en Tienen, 1168\", tr. A. Zoete, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 26\u201329.</ref>\n|-\n| 1178 ||  || [[Gislebert of Mons]] becomes chancellor to [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut]].<ref name=\"G. Wymans 1980 pp. 37\">G. Wymans, \"Oorkonde van het kapittel van Zinnik, geschreven door Gillebert van Bergen, kanselier van Henegouwen, 1198\", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 37\u201339.</ref>\n|-\n| 1184 || 1 April ||  [[Henry IV, Count of Luxembourg|Henry the Blind]], [[Count of Namur]] and [[Count of Luxembourg|of Luxembourg]], being childless, names his nephew, [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut]], already heir to all his [[allod]]ial possessions, as heir equally to all his [[fief|feudal possessions]], \"with sod and twig\", retaining [[usufruct]] during his own lifetime.<ref name=\"F. Ladrier 1980 pp. 29\"/>\n|-\n| 1186 || July || birth of [[Ermesinde, Countess of Luxembourg|Ermesinde, later countess of Luxembourg]], only child of Henry the Blind. As a female heir she would inherit his allodial possessions, but not his feudal possessions.<ref name=\"F. Ladrier 1980 pp. 29\"/>\n|-\n| 1191 || 1 August|| Death of [[Philip I, Count of Flanders|Philip of Alsace]], Count of Flanders; succession of his daughter [[Margaret I, Countess of Flanders]], and her husband and co-ruler [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut]]\n|-\n| 1192 || 21 November || Murder of [[Albert of Louvain]], [[Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]], by supporters of [[Henry VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Henry VI]]\n|-\n| 1193 || 19 May || Relics of [[Saint Alena]] enshrined in [[Forest Abbey|Forest Priory]].<ref name=\"Bart Fransen 2008 pp. 95\">Bart Fransen, \"Recherches historiques / Historisch onderzoek\", ''Bulletin'' of the [[Royal Institute for Cultural Heritage]], 32 (2006\u20132008), pp. 95\u2013101.</ref>\n|-\n| 1194 || 20 August || Peace treaty between [[Henry I, Duke of Brabant]] and [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut]], ending twelve years of conflict between the [[Duchy of Brabant]] and the [[County of Hainaut]].<ref>G. Wymans, \"Vredesverdrag tussen Hendrik I, hertog van Brabant, en Boudewijn V, graaf van Henegouwen en Vlaanderen, 1194\", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 33\u201337.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 15 November || Death of [[Margaret I, Countess of Flanders]]; her husband [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut]] continues to rule as Baldwin VIII of Flanders\n|-\n| 1195 || 17 December || Death of [[Baldwin V, Count of Hainaut]]; succession of his son [[Baldwin I of Constantinople|Baldwin]] as count of Flanders and Hainaut\n|-\n| 1198 ||  || [[Baldwin I of Constantinople|Baldwin VI]], [[Count of Hainaut]], donates all his possessions in the village of [[Horrues]] to the collegiate church of [[Soignies]] to endow a [[Lady chapel]] and a [[chantry]].<ref name=\"G. Wymans 1980 pp. 37\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n== 13th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1205 || 14 April || [[Battle of Adrianople (1205)|Battle of Adrianople]]: [[Baldwin I of Constantinople]], count of Flanders and Hainaut, captured by the [[Bulgaria]]ns\n|-\n| 1213 || 30\u201331 May || [[Battle of Damme]]: English fleet destroys French fleet at anchor near Damme.<ref>F. W. Brooks, \"The Battle of Damme, 1213\", ''Mariner's Mirror'' 16 (1930), 264\u2013271.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 13 October || [[Battle of Steppes]]: army and allies of [[Hugh Pierrepont]], [[Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]], defeat the forces of [[Henry I, Duke of Brabant]].<ref>John France, ''Western Warfare in the Age of the Crusades, 1000\u20131300'' (London, 2002), p. 166.</ref>\n|-\n| 1214 || 27 July || [[Battle of Bouvines]]: decisive French victory against the forces of [[Ferdinand, Count of Flanders]], [[Henry I, Duke of Brabant]], and [[Otto IV, Holy Roman Emperor]]. Count of Flanders carried captive to Paris.<ref>[[Georges Duby]], ''Le Dimanche de Bouvines, 27 juillet 1214'' (Gallimard, 1985).</ref>\n|-\n| 1224 || 12 August || [[Guy II, Count of Saint-Pol|Guy of Saint-Pol]] and his brother, [[Hugo V, Count of Saint-Pol|Hugo of Saint-Pol]], stand surety for a loan of 3693 pounds borrowed from citizens of [[Arras]] by [[Daniel, Lord of B\u00e9thune]]: an early example of the use of French rather than Latin in legal documents.<ref>C. Wyffels, \"Het verschijnen in ons land van Nederlands en Frans in de ambtelijke schrijftaal\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 ([[State Archives in Belgium]], Brussels, 1980), pp. 43\u201345.</ref>\n|-\n| 1232 || 20 September || [[Ferdinand, Count of Flanders]] and [[Joan, Countess of Flanders]] release inhabitants of the [[Brugse Vrije]] from the [[feudal relief]] of [[heriot|\"best beast\"]].<ref>J. Mertens, \"Vrijstelling van 'beste hoofd', 1232\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 46\u201348.</ref>\n|-\n| 1236 ||  || Statutes of the Ghent Leper Hospital translated from Latin: the earliest known example of a legal document entirely in Dutch.<ref>C. Wyffels, \"Het verschijnen in ons land van Nederlands en Frans in de ambtelijke schrijftaal\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 43\u201345.</ref>\n|-\n| 1237 ||  || Charters of the city of Ghent translated into Dutch.<ref>C. Wyffels, \"Het verschijnen in ons land van Nederlands en Frans in de ambtelijke schrijftaal\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), p. 45.</ref>\n|-\n| 1238 ||  || Benedictine priory at [[Forest, Belgium|Vorst]], a dependency of [[Affligem Abbey]], becomes the independent [[Forest Abbey]].<ref name=\"Bart Fransen 2008 pp. 95\"/>\n|-\n| 1245 || 14 June || [[Pope Innocent IV]] authorizes the [[Augustinians|canons regular of St Augustine]] to establish a grammar school in [[Leuven]].<ref>M. Grawuen, \"Inrichting van een school te Leuven, 1245\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 48\u201350.</ref>\n|-\n| 1255 ||  || Gothic choir of [[Tournai Cathedral]] completed\n|-\n| 1270 || 1 September || [[Margaret II, Countess of Flanders|Margaret of Constantinople]], [[Countess of Flanders]], impounds wares of English merchants in Flanders in retaliation for their king's non-payment of a money fief, sparking a trade war between Flanders and England.<ref name=\"C. Wyffels 1980 pp. 54\">C. Wyffels, \"Economische oorlog tussen Vlaanderen en Engeland\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 54\u201356.</ref>\n|-\n| 1274 || 28 July || [[Treaty of Montreuil (1274)|Treaty of Montreuil-sur-Mer]] between [[Edward I of England]] and [[Guy, Count of Flanders]], ending four years of economic warfare and providing for free movement of merchants between their territories.<ref name=\"C. Wyffels 1980 pp. 54\"/>\n|-\n| 1281 || 21 August || [[Guy de Thourout]] does homage to [[Guy, Count of Flanders]] for lands in [[Wervik]], [[Reninge]] and [[Rollegem]]. He also held land in [[Menen]] and [[Rekkem]], a manor in [[Varsenare]], and owned a number of houses within the city of [[Ypres]].<ref>[[Fran\u00e7ois-Louis Ganshof]], \"Gui de Thourout\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2073.pdf vol. 25] (Brussels, 1932), 141-142.</ref>\n|-\n| 1288 || 5 June || [[Battle of Worringen]]\n|-\n| 1293 || 7 May || Aldermen of [[Nieuwpoort, Belgium|Nieuwpoort]] accept the mediation of [[Guy, Count of Flanders]] in their dispute with the abbeys of [[Ten Duinen Abbey|Duinen]] and [[Bourbourg]] concerning a dyke built near the town.<ref>J. Mertens, \"Geschil over een dijk bij Nieuwpoort\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 63\u201365.</ref>\n|-\n| 1296 || 2 November || [[Edward I of England]] grants Flemish merchants the right to buy wool for export anywhere in the British Isles, rather than being limited to the [[wool staple]].<ref>J. Danhieux, \"Handel tussen Engeland en Vlaanderen, 1296\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 65\u201367.</ref>\n|-\n| 1297 || 12 June || Treaties of alliance between [[Philip IV of France]] and [[John II, Count of Holland|John of Avesnes]], [[Count of Hainaut]], culminate in a trade treaty allowing merchants from Hainaut to trade freely in the kingdom of France.<ref>C. Dumont, \"Handelsverdrag tussen Filips de Schone, koning van Frankrijk, en Jan van Avesnes, graaf van Henegouwen, 1297\", tr. H. Coppens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 68\u201369.</ref>\n|-\n| || 5 November || [[Guy, Count of Flanders]] and [[Marquis of Namur]] transfers government of [[County of Namur|Namur]] to [[John I, Marquis of Namur|John of Namur]], his eldest son by [[Isabelle of Luxembourg]], breaking the personal union of Namur with the [[County of Flanders]] (which would pass to [[Robert III, Count of Flanders|Robert]], Guy's son by [[Matilda of B\u00e9thune]]).<ref>J. Bovesse, \"Verbreking van de persoonlijke dynastieke band tussen de graafschappen Vlaanderen en Namen op het eind van de 13de eeuw\", tr. H. Coppens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 70\u201372.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== 14th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1302 || 11 July || [[Battle of the Golden Spurs]]: [[County of Flanders|Flemish]] forces defeat knights of [[Philip IV of France]] near [[Kortrijk]]\n|-\n| 1303 || 9 July || Aldermen of the [[Namur, Belgium|city of Namur]] authorize formation of a butchers' guild, with obligations to arm themselves, follow their own banner, and bury their own dead.<ref>J. Bovesse, \"Statuten van het Naamse beenhouwersambacht, 1303\", tr. E. Persoons, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 72\u201376.</ref>\n|-\n| 1312 || 27 September || The [[Charter of Kortenberg]] finalised at Kortenberg Abbey, establishing fundamental rights for the inhabitants of the [[Duchy of Brabant]] such as no punishment without trial according to due process. Council of four knights and ten representatives of the boroughs established (beginnings of representative institutions in the duchy).\n|-\n| 1323 || June || Rebellion of the commoners in maritime Flanders, sparked by [[Louis I, Count of Flanders]], ceding [[Sluis]] to [[John I, Marquis of Namur]].<ref>[[Henri Pirenne]], ''Le Soul\u00e8vement de la Flandre Maritime de 1323 \u00e0 1328'' (Brussels, 1900).</ref>\n|-\n| 1327 || 30 August || [[Pope John XXII]] provides a dispensation for the marriage of [[Philippa of Hainault]] and [[Edward III of England]]. The marriage itself took place by proxy in [[Valenciennes]] in October.<ref name=\"Keyzer 1980 pp. 76\">W. De Keyzer, \"Huwelijksdispensatie voor Edward III, koning van Engeland en Filippa van Henegouwen, 1327\", tr. E. Persoons, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 76\u201378.</ref>\n|-\n| 1328 || 24 January || Marriage of [[Philippa of Hainault]] and [[Edward III of England]] celebrated in [[York Minster]].<ref name=\"Keyzer 1980 pp. 76\"/>\n|-\n| 1328 || 23 August || [[Battle of Cassel (1328)|Battle of Cassel]]: [[Philip VI of France]] defeats Flemish rebels led by [[Nicolaas Zannekin]].<ref>L. Danhieux, \"Bruggelingen als gijzelaars in Frankrijk, 1328\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 78\u201382.</ref>\n|-\n| 1339 || 3 December || Treaty of mutual support between [[John III, Duke of Brabant]] and [[Louis I, Count of Flanders]], and the cities subject to them, providing for offensive and defensive alliance and free trade between their territories.<ref>A. Graffart, \"Verdrag van bondgenootschap tussen Brabant en Vlaanderens, 1339\", tr. S. Vervaeck, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 83\u201387.</ref>\n|-\n| 1345 || 24 July || [[Jacob van Artevelde]] killed in Ghent.<ref>[[Patricia Carson]], ''James Van Artevelde: The Man from Ghent'' (Ghent, 1980).</ref>\n|-\n| 1355 || 8 March || The boroughs of the [[Duchy of Brabant]] and the [[Duchy of Limburg]] undertake to remain united under a single prince after the death of [[John III, Duke of Brabant]], not allowing the territory to be divided among his heirs.<ref>R. Wellens, \"Verbond der steden, 1355\", tr. S. Vervaeck, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 88\u201389.</ref>\n|-\n| 1356 || 3 January || [[Joyous Entry of 1356]]: [[Joanna, Duchess of Brabant]] and her husband [[Wenceslaus I of Luxembourg]] sign the great charter of liberties of the [[Duchy of Brabant]].<ref>R. Wellens, \"Blijde Inkomst van Brabant, 1356\", tr. S. Vervaeck, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 89\u201392.</ref>\n|-\n| 1370 ||  || [[Brussels massacre|Extirpation of small Jewish population of Brabant]] after accusations of profaning eucharistic hosts.\n|-\n| 1386 || 15 February || [[Philip the Bold]] founds the [[Lille Chamber of Accounts]] to audit the accounts of his functionaries in the [[county of Flanders]].<ref>\"[http://data.bnf.fr/12555334/pays-bas_espagnols_chambre_des_comptes_lille/ Chambre des comptes. Lille] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119011920/http://data.bnf.fr/12555334/pays-bas_espagnols_chambre_des_comptes_lille/ |date=19 January 2017 }}\", data.bnf.fr (website of the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]]), last updated 7 Feb. 2017. Accessed 25 June 2017.</ref>\n|-\n| 1387 || 2 November || Oldest record of the incorporation of the [[Guilds of Brussels|Brussels guild]] of painters, goldbeaters and glassmakers.<ref>A. Graffart, \"Register van het schilders-, goudslagers- en glazenmakersambacht van Brussel, 1707\u20131794\", tr. M. Erkens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), p. 268.</ref>\n|-\n| 1389 ||  || [[John III, Duke of Bavaria|John of Bavaria]] elected [[Prince-Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]] (resigned 1418).\n|-\n| 1390 || 28 September || [[Joanna, Duchess of Brabant]] secretly relinquishes possession of the [[Duchy of Brabant]] to her niece, [[Margaret III, Countess of Flanders|Margaret of Male]], and offspring thereof.<ref>A. Van Nieuwenhuysen, \"De erfopvolging in Brabant, 1392\", tr. S. Vervaeck, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1, tr. J. Verhelst, (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 97\u201399.</ref>\n|-\n| 1392 ||1 November || [[John III, Duke of Bavaria|John of Bavaria]], [[Prince-Bishop of Liege|bishop-elect of Li\u00e8ge]], writes to [[Philip the Bold]] to intercede for merchants from [[Li\u00e8ge]] arrested by the officers of [[Rethel]].<ref>G. Hansotte, \"De betrekkingen tussen Luikenaren en Bourgondi\u00ebrs in de XIVde eeuw\", tr. J. Verhelst, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 99\u2013100.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n== 15th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1408 || 9 September || [[John the Fearless]] takes fiscal measures to pay [[Alexander Stewart, Earl of Mar]]'s archers joining him on the Li\u00e8ge campaign. (Letter bearing only known surviving signature of John the Fearless).<ref>A. Zoete, \"Brief van Jan zonder Vrees, 1408\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 103\u2013106.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 28 September || [[Battle of Oth\u00e9e]]: forces of [[John the Fearless]] and [[John III, Duke of Bavaria|John of Bavaria]] defeat Li\u00e8ge rebels.\n|-\n| 1421 || 23 April || [[Philip the Good]] transfers [[usufruct]] of the [[County of Namur]] to John of Flanders, Lord of B\u00e9thune, for the duration of his life.<ref>J. Bovesse, \"Verkoop van het graafschap Namen wan Filips de Goede, heritage van Bourgondi\u00eb, 1421\", tr. J. Verhelst, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 108\u2013111.</ref>\n|-\n| 1425 || 9 December || [[Pope Martin V]] issues papal bull founding [[Old University of Leuven|University of Leuven]].\n|-\n| 1441 ||  || [[Tapestry]] weavers of [[Oudenaarde]] form the Guild of St Barbara.<ref>G. gadijn, \"Wandtapijtkunst te Oudenaarde, 1596\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 190\u2013192.</ref>\n|-\n| 1451 || 28 October || Guilds of [[Ghent]] [[Revolt of Ghent (1449\u201353)|take up arms]] against the Count of Flanders, [[Philip the Good]].\n|-\n| 1452 || 31 May || [[Philip the Good]] declares war on the city of [[Ghent]].\n|-\n| 1453 || 23 July || [[Battle of Gavere]]: forces of [[Philip the Good]] defeat rebels of [[Ghent]], ending [[Revolt of Ghent (1449\u201353)|their rebellion]].\n|-\n| 1454 || 17 February || The [[Feast of the Pheasant]], a banquet given by [[Philip the Good]], Duke of Burgundy, held in [[Lille]].\n|-\n| 1464 || 9 January\u201312 February || [[Estates General of 1464]]: first joint meeting of representatives of various territories of the [[Burgundian Netherlands]].<ref>[[Wim Blockmans]], \"De samenstelling van de staten van de Bourgondische landsheerlijkheden omstreeks 1464\", ''Standen en Landen'' 47 (1968), pp. 57\u2013112.</ref>\n|-\n| 1465 || 20 October || [[Battle of Montenaken]]: forces of [[Philip the Good]] defeat Li\u00e8ge militiamen.<ref name=Marchandise>Alain Marchandise, Ir\u00e8ne Vrancken-Pirson and Jean-Louis Kupper, \"[https://orbi.ulg.ac.be/bitstream/2268/185181/1/Sac%20Li\u00e8ge.pdf La destruction de la ville de Li\u00e8ge (1468) et sa reconstruction]\", in ''Destruction et reconstruction de villes, du moyen \u00e2ge \u00e0 nos jours'' (Brussels, 1999).</ref>{{rp|72\u201373}}\n|-\n|  || 22 December || [[Treaty of Saint-Trond]] ends hostilities between Li\u00e8ge and Burgundy, subjecting the [[prince-bishopric of Li\u00e8ge]] to Burgundian control.{{r|Marchandise|p=72-73}}\n|-\n| 1466 || 19 to 25 August 1466 || Dinant sacked by the forces of [[Philip the Good]], commanded by [[Charles the Bold]]\n|-\n| 1467 || 15 June || Death of [[Philip the Good]]; [[Charles the Bold]] succeeds as [[Duke of Burgundy]].\n|-\n|  || 28 October || [[Battle of Brustem]]: forces of [[Charles the Bold]] defeat forces of Li\u00e8ge.\n|-\n|  || 12 November || City of Li\u00e8ge surrenders to [[Charles the Bold]].\n|-\n| 1468 || 3 July || Marriage of [[Charles the Bold]] and [[Margaret of York]] (Now commemorated with the five-yearly [[Procession of the Golden Tree]])\n|-\n|  || September || Li\u00e8ge again rises against Burgundian rule.{{r|Marchandise|p=74}}\n|-\n|  || 27 October || Army of [[Charles the Bold]] reaches Li\u00e8ge.{{r|Marchandise|p=78}}\n|-\n|  || 29 October || [[Six hundred Franchimontois]] raid the Burgundian encampment outside Li\u00e8ge, failing to dislodge besiegers.{{r|Marchandise|p=79}}\n|-\n|  || 30 October to 2 November || City of Li\u00e8ge pillaged by Burgundian troops.\n|-\n|  || 3 November || [[Charles the Bold]] orders the city of Li\u00e8ge systematically razed, sparing only the churches and the houses of [[canon (priest)|canons]].{{r|Marchandise|p=84}}\n|-\n| 1469 || 1 July || [[Charles the Bold]] grants [[Louis de Bourbon, Bishop of Li\u00e8ge|Prince-Bishop Louis of Bourbon]] permission to begin rebuilding Li\u00e8ge.{{r|Marchandise|p=86-87}}\n|-\n| 1473 || 24 April || [[Charles the Bold]] appointed mediator in the peace negotiations between Poland and Hungary.<ref>J. Verhelst, \"Vredesonderhandelingen tussen Polen en Hongarije, 1473\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 112\u2013113.</ref>\n|-\n|  || December || [[Charles the Bold]] overhauls the administrative structures of the [[Burgundian Netherlands]]: establishes [[Great Council of Mechelen]]; orders the chambers of accounts of [[Lille]] and [[Brussels]] be combined and sit in [[Mechelen]].<ref>D. Van Derveeghde, \"Poging tot reorganisatie en centralisatie van de financi\u00ebn onder Karel de Stoute, 1473\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 113\u2013115.</ref>\n|-\n| 1477 || 5 January || [[Charles the Bold]] dies in the [[Battle of Nancy]].\n|-\n|  || 29 May || [[Joyous Entry]] of [[Mary of Burgundy]] in [[Leuven]] as [[Duchess of Brabant]].<ref>R. Wellens, \"Blijde Inkomst in Brabant, 1477\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 115\u2013117.</ref>\n|-\n|  || 18 August || [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian of Austria]] makes his entry into Ghent.\n|-\n|  || 19 August || Marriage between [[Mary of Burgundy]] and [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian of Austria]] celebrated.\n|-\n| 1478 || 22 July || Birth of [[Philip I of Castile|Philip the Fair]]\n|-\n| 1479 || 7 August || [[Battle of Guinegate (1479)|Battle of Guinegate]]: forces of [[Mary of Burgundy]] and her husband [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I of Habsburg]] defeat forces of [[Louis XI of France]].\n|-\n| 1480 || 10 January || Birth of [[Margaret of Austria, Duchess of Savoy|Margaret of Burgundy]]\n|-\n| 1482 || 27 March || [[Mary of Burgundy]] dies as a result of having fallen from her horse while hawking some weeks earlier. Leaving an infant heir and a foreign husband, this set the scene for the [[Flemish revolts against Maximilian of Austria]] (1483\u20131485).\n|-\n|  || 3 April || Funeral of [[Mary of Burgundy]] in [[Church of Our Lady, Bruges]]\n|-\n|  || 30 August || [[Louis de Bourbon, Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]] assassinated by [[William de La Marck]].\n|-\n|  || 19 November || Six women burned at the stake in Bruges for having committed \"sodomy\" with women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eoswetenschap.eu/geschiedenis/lesbisch-de-middeleeuwen-tamelijk-veilig-behalve-hier|author=Jonas Roelens|title=Lesbisch in de middeleeuwen? Tamelijk veilig behalve hier|language=nl|date=16 September 2019|website=EOS wetenschap}}</ref>\n|-\n|  || 23 December || [[Treaty of Arras (1482)|Treaty of Arras]] between [[Louis XI of France]] and [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I of Habsburg]] as heir of the [[Burgundian Netherlands]], ceding Burgundy and Artois to France.\n|-\n|  || || Oldest surviving [[parish register]] from the territory of what is now Belgium: marriage register from the [[Cathedral of St. Michael and St. Gudula|Church of St Gudula]] in Brussels.<ref name=\"A. Libois 1980 pp. 179\">A. Libois, \"Tekening in een parochieregister: het huwelijk\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 179\u2013190.</ref>\n|-\n| 1493 || 23 May || [[Treaty of Senlis]]: [[Charles VIII of France]] cedes the [[County of Flanders]] and [[County of Artois]] to the [[House of Habsburg]].<ref>U. Vermeuelen, \"Bekrachtiging van het verdrag van Senlis, 1493\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 118\u2013119.</ref>\n|-\n| 1495 || 20 January || Wedding contracts concluded for the double marriage of [[Philip I of Castile|Philip the Fair]] and [[Margaret of Austria, Duchess of Savoy|Margaret of Burgundy]] to  [[Joanna of Castile]] and [[John, Prince of Asturias]].<ref name=\"Joni M. Hand 2013 p. 84\">Joni M. Hand, ''Women, Manuscripts and Identity in Northern Europe, 1350\u20131550'' (Ashgate, 2013), p. 84</ref>\n|-\n|  || 5 November || Double wedding by proxy of [[Philip I of Castile|Philip the Fair]] and [[Margaret of Austria, Duchess of Savoy|Margaret of Burgundy]] to [[Joanna of Castile]] and [[John, Prince of Asturias]].<ref name=\"Joni M. Hand 2013 p. 84\"/>\n|-\n|-\n| 1500 || 24 February || Birth of the future [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]], in [[Ghent]].\n|-\n|  || 7 March || Christening of the future [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]], in [[Ghent]], with [[Margaret of York]], [[Margaret of Austria, Duchess of Savoy|Margaret of Austria]], [[Charles I de Cro\u00ff|Charles, Prince of Chimay]], and [[John III of Bergen op Zoom|John, Lord of Bergen op Zoom]] as godparents.<ref name=Meerbeeck>[[Adriaan van Meerbeeck]], ''Chronijcke vande gantsche Werelt'' (Antwerp, 1620).</ref>{{rp|3}}\n|-\n|  || May || [[Philip I of Castile|Philip of Burgundy]] received as ruler in [[B\u00e9thune]], [[Saint-Omer]] and [[Dunkirk]].{{r|Meerbeeck|p=4}}\n|-\n|  || 9 June || Conference outside [[Calais]] between [[Henry VII of England]] and [[Philip I of Castile|Philip of Burgundy]].{{r|Meerbeeck|p=4}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== 16th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1501 || 18 July || Birth of [[Isabella of Austria]], daughter of [[Philip I of Castile|Philip of Burgundy]] and [[Joanna of Castile]], future Queen of [[Christian II of Denmark]].\n|-\n| 1509 || 25 June || [[Pope Julius II]] grants [[indulgence]] for those contributing to the rebuilding of the [[Notre Dame de Dinant|collegiate church of Dinant]], equal to the indulgence for a [[Seven Pilgrim Churches of Rome|pilgrimage to Rome]].<ref name=\"A. Smolar-Meynart 1980 pp. 122\">A. Smolar-Meynart, \"Aflaatbul voor de wederopbouw van de collegiale kerk van Onze-Lieve-Vrouw the Dinant, 1509\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 122\u2013124.</ref>\n|-\n| 1511 || 2 April || [[\u00c9rard de La Marck]], [[Prince-Bishop of Li\u00e8ge]], orders publication of Julius II's bull granting an indulgence for those contributing to the rebuilding of the [[Notre Dame de Dinant|collegiate church of Dinant]].<ref name=\"A. Smolar-Meynart 1980 pp. 122\"/>\n|-\n| 1521 || 8 May || [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] issues decree for the [[Habsburg Netherlands]] prohibiting Lutheran preaching, teaching, printing or disputation, largely parallel to the [[Edict of Worms]] that he was to sign for the Empire as a whole on 26 May but providing more repressive powers to secular authorities.<ref>E. Persoons, \"Edikt van Worms, 8 mei 1521. Speciale tekst voor de Nederlanden. France versie\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 124\u2013126.</ref>\n|-\n| 1523 || 1 July || [[Johann Esch and Heinrich Voes]] burned at the stake in [[Brussels]] for their adherence to [[Lutheran]] doctrines.<ref name=\"E. Persoons 1980 pp. 150\">E. Persoons, \"Edikten of 'placcaten' van Karel V tegen het Lutheranisme\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 150\u2013153.</ref>\n|-\n| || 8 September || [[Pope Adrian VI]] draws up a [[last will and testament]] to dispose of his possessions in the [[Habsburg Netherlands]], among other bequests founding [[Pope's College, Leuven|a papal college]] for students of Theology at the [[Old University of Leuven|University of Leuven]].<ref>M. Grauwen, \"Testament van paus Adriaan VI, 1523\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 127\u2013129.</ref>\n|-\n| 1526 || 14 January || [[Treaty of Madrid (1526)|Peace of Madrid]] temporarily ends the war between [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] and [[Francis I of France]], with France briefly relinquishing all claim to the [[County of Flanders]], [[County of Artois]], [[Tournai and the Tournaisis]], and the [[Duchy of Burgundy]].<ref>U. Vermeulen, \"Vrede van Madrid, 1526\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 129\u2013130.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1531 in Belgium|1531]] || 26 September || [[Mary of Hungary]] appointed regent over the [[Habsburg Netherlands]].<ref>J. Buntinx, \"Maria van Hongarije landvoogdes, 1531\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 131\u2013132.</ref>\n|-\n| 1532 || 11 September || Charles V issues decree establishing protocols and procedure of the reorganized Council of Luxembourg.<ref name=\"R. Petit 1980 pp. 132\">R. Petit, \"Keizerlijke verordening houdend reglement van de Raad van Luxemburg, 1532\", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 132\u2013141.</ref>\n|-\n| 1540 || 4 October || New edict requiring printers and booksellers to provide local magistrates with inventories of their stock.<ref name=\"E. Persoons 1980 pp. 150\"/>\n|-\n| 1546 || 9 May || [[Old University of Leuven|University of Leuven]] issues the first [[Index Librorum Prohibitorum|index of prohibited books]].<ref name=\"E. Persoons 1980 pp. 150\"/>\n|-\n| 1542 || August || French forces plunder [[Arlon]].<ref name=\"R. Petit 1980 pp. 156\">R. Petit, \"Rekwest van de burgers van Aarlen tot het bekomen van de alleenhandel in de proosdij, 1548\", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 156\u2013159.</ref>\n|-\n| || 1 September || [[Francis I of France]] appoints [[Claude, Duke of Guise]] as governor of the [[Duchy of Luxembourg]].\n|-\n| 1544 ||  || [[Italian War of 1542\u201346#Treaty of Cr\u00e9py|Peace of Cr\u00e9py]] ends the war between [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] and [[Francis I of France]], returning status quo of 1538: [[Duchy of Luxembourg]] restored to the [[Habsburg Netherlands]].<ref name=\"R. Petit 1980 pp. 156\"/>\n|-\n| 1549 || 12 September || Edict regulating the organization of markets throughout the [[Habsburg Netherlands]].<ref name=\"R. Petit 1980 pp. 156\"/>\n|-\n| 1566 || 5 April || [[Compromise of Nobles]] petition [[Margaret of Parma]] to suspend the laws on heresy.<ref name=\"Stobbeleir 1980 pp. 164\">D. De Stobbeleir, \"Het eedverbond der edelen, 1565\u20131566\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 164\u2013169.</ref>\n|-\n| || 31 July || [[Philip II of Spain]] authorises [[Margaret of Parma]] to abolish the inquisition in the [[Habsburg Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Stobbeleir 1980 pp. 164\"/>\n|-\n| || August to September || [[Beeldenstorm|Iconoclastic Fury]]: churches and monasteries vandalised and plundered in many parts of the [[Habsburg Netherlands]].\n|-\n| 1567 || 15 March || Attempted [[Calvinist]] coup in [[Antwerp]].<ref name=\"H. Delvaux 1980 pp. 171\">H. Delvaux, \"Veroordeling van Antwerpse hervormden, 1568\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 171\u2013173.</ref>\n|-\n|  || June || [[Margaret of Parma]] reinstitutes suspended edicts against heresy.<ref name=\"Stobbeleir 1980 pp. 164\"/>\n|-\n| 1568 || 18 May || [[Fernando \u00c1lvarez de Toledo, 3rd Duke of Alba|Duke of Alva]] banishes thirty inhabitants of the city of [[Antwerp]] and their spouses, with forfeiture of property, for supporting or disseminating [[Calvinism]] \u2013 including the [[pensionary]] of the city, Jacques van Wesenbeke, and the head of the Calvinist [[Consistory (Protestantism)|consistory]] in Antwerp, the Portuguese merchant Marcus Perez.<ref name=\"H. Delvaux 1980 pp. 171\"/>\n|-\n| 1569 || 17 May || [[Maximilien Morillon]] founds the first diocesan seminary in [[Mechelen]].<ref>[[Charles Piot (archivist)|Charles Piot]], \"Morillon (maximilien)\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [https://www.academieroyale.be/Academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2057.pdf vol. 15] (Brussels 1899), 267-272.</ref>\n|-\n| 1574 || 6 June || [[Luis de Requesens y Z\u00fa\u00f1iga|Don Luis de Requesens]], [[Governor of the Habsburg Netherlands]], issues general pardon to rebels willing to return to loyalty.<ref name=\"Stobbeleir 1980 pp. 164\"/>\n|-\n| 1570 || 30 May || [[Abraham Ortelius]]' ''[[Theatrum Orbis Terrarum]]'' published in Antwerp.\n|-\n| 1575 || 16 June || [[Philip II of Spain]] decrees that the change of year is to be counted from 1 January throughout the [[Habsburg Netherlands]], rather than from [[Christmas day]] (25 December), the [[Feast of the Annunciation]] (25 March) or [[Easter day]], as was the custom in various parts.<ref>J. De Keyzer, \"Kalenderhervorming in de Spaanse Nederlanden, 1575\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 173\u2013176.</ref>\n|-\n| 1576 || 4 November || [[Sack of Antwerp]] by Spanish mutineers from the [[Army of Flanders]] \n|-\n|  || 8 November || [[Pacification of Ghent]]: alliance of the provinces of the [[Habsburg Netherlands]] to drive mutineers from the [[Army of Flanders]] from the country and promote a peace treaty with the rebellious provinces [[Holland]] and [[Zeeland]]\n|-\n| 1579 || 6 January || [[Union of Arras]] concluded.<ref>Hugo De Schepper, \"De Nederlanden, 1550\u20141604\", in ''De val van het Nieuwe Troje: Het beleg van Oostende, 1601\u20131604'', ed. Werner Thomas (Ostend and Leuven, 2004), p. 22.</ref> \n|-\n| 1596 || 24 April || [[Albert VII of Austria|Archduke Albert]] [[Siege of Calais (1596)|takes Calais]].<ref name=\"Etienne Rooms 2004 p. 35\">Luc De Vos and Etienne Rooms, \"Tactisch een Staats, strategisch een Paaps succes\", in ''De val van het Nieuwe Troje: Het beleg van Oostende, 1601\u20131604'', ed. Werner Thomas (Ostend and Leuven, 2004), p. 35.</ref>\n|-\n| || 18 August || [[Albert VII of Austria|Archduke Albert]] [[Siege of Hulst (1596)|takes Hulst]].<ref name=\"Etienne Rooms 2004 p. 35\"/>\n|-\n| 1597 || 11 March || [[Army of Flanders]] takes Amiens.<ref name=\"Etienne Rooms 2004 p. 35\"/>\n|-\n| || 10 September || [[Philip II of Spain]] decides to bequeath his lands in the Low Countries and Burgundy to his daughter, [[Isabella Clara Eugenia]].<ref>Hugo De Schepper, \"De Nederlanden, 1550\u20141604\", in ''De val van het Nieuwe Troje: Het beleg van Oostende, 1601\u20131604'', ed. Werner Thomas (Ostend and Leuven, 2004), p. 25.</ref> \n|-\n| 1598 || 2 May || [[Peace of Vervins]] signed.<ref name=\"Etienne Rooms 2004 p. 35\"/>\n|-\n| || 6 May || [[Philip II of Spain]] signs the Act of Cession bequeathing the [[Habsburg Netherlands]] to his daughter, the [[Isabella Clara Eugenia|Infanta Isabella]].<ref name=\"Etienne Rooms 2004 p. 35\"/>\n|-\n| || 13 September || [[Philip II of Spain]] dies.\n|-\n| || 14 September || [[Albert VII of Austria|Archduke Albert]] departs from Brussels to marry the [[Isabella Clara Eugenia|Infanta Isabella]].<ref n