as new governor general.<ref>{{Royal Collection|400100|Description of ''The Battle of N\u00f6rdlingen'' (1634)|[[Jan van den Hoecke]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1635 in Belgium|1635]] || May to July || Beginning of hostilities in the [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u201359)]]: [[Battle of Les Avins]], [[Sack of Tienen]], [[Siege of Leuven]]\n|-\n| [[1637 in Belgium|1637]] || 17 April || Exiled Dutch nobleman [[Ren\u00e9 de Renesse, 1st Count of Warfus\u00e9e]], has the mayor of Li\u00e8ge, [[S\u00e9bastien de La Ruelle]], murdered by Spanish soldiers.<ref>[[Henri Lonchay]], \"La Ruelle (S\u00e9bastien de)\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www2.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2052.pdf vol. 11] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220100252/http://www.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2052.pdf |date=20 December 2016 }} (Brussels, 1891), 374.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1638 in Belgium|1638]] || 24 May to 16 July || [[Siege of Saint-Omer]]: French army fails to take the city of [[Saint-Omer]]\n|-\n| || 20 June || [[Battle of Kallo]]: [[Cardinal-Infante Ferdinand of Austria]] prevents Dutch forces from encircling [[Antwerp]].\n|-\n| [[1639 in Belgium|1639]] || 7 June || [[Relief of Thionville]]: imperial forces under [[Ottavio Piccolomini]] break the French siege of [[Thionville]] in the [[Duchy of Luxembourg]]\n|-\n| [[1648 in Belgium|1648]] || 15 May || [[Peace of M\u00fcnster]] ends the war with the [[Dutch Republic]].\n|-\n| [[1658 in Belgium|1658]] || 14 June || [[Battle of the Dunes (1658)|Battle of the Dunes]]: the [[Army of Flanders]] and British Royalist allies fail to raise the French-Cromwellian [[Siege of Dunkirk (1658)|Siege of Dunkirk]], leading to the loss of the city.\n|-\n| [[1695 in Belgium|1695]] || 2 July to 1 September || [[Siege of Namur (1695)|Siege of Namur]]\n|-\n| || 13\u201315 August || [[Bombardment of Brussels]] by the army of [[Louis XIV]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== 18th century ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"100%\"\n! style=\"width:6%\" | Year || style=\"width:15%\" | Date || Event\n|-\n| 1704 || 20 June || Edict in the name of [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor]], reorganises office of [[Civil law notary|notary]] in the Habsburg Netherlands.<ref>A. Libois, \"Huwelijkskontrakt tussen Amand Thirion en Marie Joseph Fontaine, 1733\", tr. M. Grauwen, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 234\u2013241.</ref>\n|-\n| 1713 || 29 January || Second [[Barrier Treaty]] confirms the closing of the Scheldt.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\">J. Mertens, \"Oostende \u2013 Kanton \u2013 Oostende, 1719\u20131720\", in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 224\u2013228.</ref>\n|-\n| 1714 || 6 March || [[Treaty of Rastatt]] signed: hostilities between France and Austria arising from [[War of the Spanish Succession]] cease; [[Spanish Netherlands]] become [[Austrian Netherlands]].<ref>M. Soenen, \"Gedrukte tekst van het Verdrag van Rastadt, 1714\", tr. M. Erkens, in ''Doorheen de nationale geschiedenis'', vol. 1 (State Archives in Belgium, Brussels, 1980), pp. 219\u2013222.</ref>\n|-\n| 1715 || || Start of Flemish China trade.<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n| 1719 || 5 February || The ''Saint-Joseph'' sets sail from [[Ostend]] for [[Guangzhou|Canton]].<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n|  || 3 August || The ''Saint-Joseph'', from [[Ostend]], arrives in [[Guangzhou|Canton]].<ref name=\"J. Mertens 1980 pp. 224\"/>\n|-\n|  || 19 September || [[Frans Anneessens]], dean of the masons' guild, beheaded in Brussels for resisting innovations in city government detrimental to the power of the [[guilds of Brussels]].<ref>[[Alphonse Wauters]], \"Anneessens, Fran\u00e7ois\", ''[[Biographie Nationale de Belgique]]'', [http://www2.academieroyale.be/academie/documents/FichierPDFBiographieNationaleTome2037.pdf vol. 1] {{Webarchive