London 1870 p. 76\">[[William Henry Overall]], ''The dictionary of chronology, or historical and statistical register'' (London, 1870), p. 76.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1815 in Belgium|1815]] || 16 June || [[Battle of Ligny]]: Napoleon Bonaparte's last victory.\n|-\n| || 18 June || [[Battle of Waterloo]]: final defeat of Napoleon Bonaparte.\n|-\n| [[1822 in Belgium|1822]] || || [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale de Belgique|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale]] founded\n|-\n| [[1830 in Belgium|1830]] || 25 August || [[Belgian Revolution]] begins\n|-\n| || 26 December || Allied powers recognise Belgian independence.<ref name=\"London 1870 p. 76\"/>\n|-\n| [[1831 in Belgium|1831]]  || 21 July || [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold, Prince of Coburg]], sworn in as king of the Belgians.<ref name=\"William Henry Overall 1870 p. 76\">William Henry Overall, ''The dictionary of chronology, or historical and statistical register'' (London, 1870), p. 76.</ref>\n|-\n| || 2\u201312 August|| [[Ten Days' Campaign]]: Dutch attempt to re-establish rule over Belgium fails, but Dutch forces retain control of [[Antwerp Citadel]].\n|-\n| [[1832 in Belgium|1832]] || 20 October || [[Albert Joseph Goblet d'Alviella]] replaces [[F\u00e9lix de Muelenaere]] as Prime Minister\n|-\n| || 15 November to 23 December || [[Siege of Antwerp (1832)|Siege of Antwerp]] by Belgian army with French support forces Dutch from [[Antwerp Citadel]].\n|-\n| [[1834 in Belgium|1834]] || 4 August || [[Barth\u00e9l\u00e9my de Theux de Meylandt]] replaces [[Albert Joseph Goblet d'Alviella]] as Prime Minister\n|-\n| [[1835 in Belgium|1835]] || 9 June || [[1835 Belgian general election|Partial legislative elections]] held.\n|-\n| [[1836 in Belgium|1836]] || 18 June || Belgium adopts the [[metric system]].{{r|Kroniek|p=627}}\n|-\n| [[1837 in Belgium|1837]] || 28 December || [[Pastoral letter]] of Belgian bishops deprecates Catholic membership of masonic lodges.{{r|Kroniek|p=628}}\n|-\n| [[1838 in Belgium|1838]] || || [[Hendrik C