dding of King Leopold III of Belgium and [[Astrid of Sweden]].\n|-\n| [[1929 in Belgium|1929]] || 10 January || ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' first published in ''[[Le Petit Vingti\u00e8me]]''\n|-\n|  || 26 May || [[Belgian general election, 1929]]\n|-\n| [[1930 in Belgium|1930]] || 3 May to 3 November || [[Exposition of 1930 (Li\u00e8ge)|Exposition internationale]] held in [[Li\u00e8ge]]\n|-\n|  || 7 September || Birth of future king [[Baudouin of Belgium]]\n|-\n| [[1931 in Belgium|1931]] || 12 May || [[Eug\u00e8ne Ysa\u00ffe]] dies.\n|-\n| [[1932 in Belgium|1932]] || 27 November || [[Belgian general election, 1932]]\n|-\n| [[1933 in Belgium|1933]] || 20 February || Convention regarding Establishment and Labour signed at Geneva, establishing [[freedom of movement|free movement of labour]] between Belgium and the Netherlands.<ref>Daniel C. Turack, \"Freedom of Movement and the Travel Document in Benelux\", ''[[International and Comparative Law Quarterly]]'', 17:1 (Jan. 1968), p. 192.</ref>\n|-\n| [[1934 in Belgium|1934]] || 17 February || Death of [[Albert I of Belgium|Albert I]], King of the Belgians.\n|-\n| || 6 June || Birth of King [[Albert II of Belgium]]\n|-\n| [[1935 in Belgium|1935]] || 27 April to 6 November || [[Brussels International Exposition (1935)]] held in Heysel, near Brussels.\n|-\n| || 29 August || [[Astrid of Sweden|Queen Astrid]] dies in a car crash\n|-\n| [[1936 in Belgium|1936]] || 24 May || [[Belgian general election, 1936]]\n|-\n| [[1937 in Belgium|1937]] || 22\u201325 May || [[Baudouin of Belgium|King Baudouin]] makes a state visit to Britain.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Belgium's Policy. King's Visit. Vital Talks. Neutrality and Colonies|url=http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/17354555|newspaper=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=24 March 1937|page=17|accessdate=27 June 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[1939 in Belgium|1939]] || 2 April || [[Belgian general election, 1939]]\n|-\n|  || 30 July || [[Exposition internationale de l'eau]] opens in [[Li\u00e